{"title_page": "Retrato Em Branco E Preto", "text_new": "\"'''Retrato Em Branco E Preto'''\" (aka \"'''Portrait in Black and White'''\" and \"'''Zingaro'''\") is a Brazilian song composed by [[Ant\u00f4nio Carlos Jobim]], with lyrics in Portuguese by [[Chico Buarque]].\n \nJobim wrote the song in 1965 as an instrumental piece entitled \"Zingaro,\" which means \"[[Names of the Romani people|gypsy]].\" In a later interview, Jobim said, \"It was the story of a musician who eventually has to pawn his violin, has no place to work, is left without his music, totally empty- handed.\"<ref name=PJobim>Jobim, Paulo, ''Cancioneiro Jobim: Antonio Carlos Jobim: biografia'', Jobim Music, Rio de Janeiro, 2002. {{ISBN|9788588757028}}.</ref> He released the instrumental version on his 1967 album ''[[A Certain Mr. Jobim]].''\n \nSoon after, he approached Chico Buarque about writing lyrics for the song. Biographer Helena Jobim says that \"Tom repeated the theme of 'Zingaro' over and over again, and loads of images, words, sounds, and harmonies came to both musicians.... Buarque recorded the melody on tape to elaborate on the verses at home. It was the first time they ever cowrote a song.... In this case, his verses were ready in just a few days.\u201d <ref name=Jobim>Jobim, Helena, ''Antonio Carlos Jobim: An Illuminated Man'', Hal Leonard, Montclair, NJ, 2011. {{ISBN|9781617803437}}></ref>\n\nThe new piece was re-titled \"Retrato Em Branco E Preto,\" which translates into English as \"Portrait in White and Black.\" Jobim asked Buarque why he reversed the usual word order of \"black and white\". Buarque responded that if he had written \"preto e branco\" (black and white), the only word that would have rhymed was \"tamanco,\" a kind of [[clog]].<ref name= Homem >Homem, Wagner, '' Hist\u00f3rias de can\u00e7\u00f5es: Chico Buarque'', Leya, S\u00e3o Paulo, Brazil, 2009. {{ISBN|9788562936029}} (Brazil edition)></ref> The work in English, however, is known as \"Portrait in Black and White.\"\n\nChico Buarque released the first recording of the song with lyrics on his 1968 album ''Chico Buarque de Hollanda (Vol. 3).''\n\n===English Version===\nAn authorized [[English language|English]] [[translation]], ''[http://www.johanchristherschutz.net/lyrics.php?do=view&id=300005 Picture in Black and White]'' was released in 2011 by [[Sweden|Swedish]] singer Nina Ripe on her debut album Apaixonada<ref>Nina Ripe's official website: http://www.ninaripe.com/apaixonada.php</ref> which was nominated for Best Album of the Year by Swedish jazz magazine Orkesterjournalen.<ref>Orkesterjournalen's website (2011): https://orkesterjournalen.com/wordpress/?p=3906</ref> The lyrics, which were very close to the original, were written by singer and songwriter [[Johan Christher Sch\u00fctz]].<ref>The full English lyrics on Sch\u00fctz website: http://www.jcschutz.com/lyrics.php?do=view&id=300005</ref>\n\n== Recorded Versions==\n* [[Ant\u00f4nio Carlos Jobim]] \u2013 ''[[A Certain Mr. Jobim]]'' (1967), as the instrumental \"Zingaro,\" and ''In\u00e9dito'' (rec. 1987, released 1995)\n* [[Chico Buarque]] \u2013 ''Chico Buarque de Hollanda (Vol. 3)'' (1968)\n* [[Nara Le\u00e3o]] \u2013 ''[[Dez Anos Depois]]'' (1971)\n* [[Elis Regina]] & [[Ant\u00f4nio Carlos Jobim]] \u2013 ''[[Elis & Tom]]'' (1974)\n* [[Stan Getz]] with [[Jo\u00e3o Gilberto]] \u2013 ''[[The Best of Two Worlds]]'' (1975)\n* Stan Getz & Jo\u00e3o Gilberto \u2013 ''[[Getz/Gilberto '76]]'' (rec. 1976, released 2016)\n* Jo\u00e3o Gilberto \u2013 ''[[Amoroso (album)|Amoroso]]'' (1976), as \"Zingaro,\" ''[[Jo\u00e3o Gilberto Prado Pereira de Oliveira (album)|Jo\u00e3o Gilberto Prado Pereira de Oliveira]]'' (1980) and ''[[Live in Montreux]]'' (rec. 1985, released 1987)\n* [[G\u00e1bor Szab\u00f3]] \u2013 ''[[Femme Fatale (G\u00e1bor Szab\u00f3 album)|Femme Fatale]]'' (rec. 1979, released 1981), as \"Zingaro\"\n* [[Joe Henderson]] \u2013 ''[[Double Rainbow: The Music of Antonio Carlos Jobim]]'' (1995)\n* [[Paquito D'Rivera]] \u2013 ''[[Brazilian Dreams]]'' (2002)\n* [[Emilie-Claire Barlow]] \u2013 ''[[Like a Lover]]'' (2005)\n* [[Toninho Horta]] - ''To Jobim with Love'' (2008)\n* [[Chick Corea]] & [[Stefano Bollani]] \u2013 ''[[Orvieto (album)|Orvieto]]'' (2011)\n* [[Chet Baker]] \u2013 ''Sings And Plays From The Film \"Let's Get Lost\"'' (1989) and ''Chet Baker In Tokyo'' (1987)\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.johanchristherschutz.net/lyrics.php?do=view&id=300005 Lyrics for the authorized English version]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Songs with music by Ant\u00f4nio Carlos Jobim]]\n[[Category:Bossa nova songs]]\n[[Category:Brazilian songs]]\n", "text_old": "\"'''Retrato Em Branco E Preto'''\" (aka \"'''Portrait in Black and White'''\" and \"'''Zingaro'''\") is a Brazilian song composed by [[Ant\u00f4nio Carlos Jobim]], with lyrics in Portuguese by [[Chico Buarque]].\n \nJobim wrote the song in 1965 as an instrumental piece entitled \"Zingaro,\" which means \"[[Names of the Romani people|gypsy]].\" In a later interview, Jobim said, \"It was the story of a musician who eventually has to pawn his violin, has no place to work, is left without his music, totally empty- handed.\"<ref name=PJobim>Jobim, Paulo, ''Cancioneiro Jobim: Antonio Carlos Jobim: biografia'', Jobim Music, Rio de Janeiro, 2002. {{ISBN|9788588757028}}.</ref> He released the instrumental version on his 1967 album ''[[A Certain Mr. Jobim]].''\n \nSoon after, he approached Chico Buarque about writing lyrics for the song. Biographer Helena Jobim says that \"Tom repeated the theme of 'Zingaro' over and over again, and loads of images, words, sounds, and harmonies came to both musicians.... Buarque recorded the melody on tape to elaborate on the verses at home. It was the first time they ever cowrote a song.... In this case, his verses were ready in just a few days.\u201d <ref name=Jobim>Jobim, Helena, ''Antonio Carlos Jobim: An Illuminated Man'', Hal Leonard, Montclair, NJ, 2011. {{ISBN|9781617803437}}></ref>\n\nThe new piece was re-titled \"Retrato Em Branco E Preto,\" which translates into English as \"Portrait in White and Black.\" Jobim asked Buarque why he reversed the usual word order of \"black and white\". Buarque responded that if he had written \"preto e branco\" (black and white), the only word that would have rhymed was \"tamanco,\" a kind of [[clog]].<ref name= Homem >Homem, Wagner, '' Hist\u00f3rias de can\u00e7\u00f5es: Chico Buarque'', Leya, S\u00e3o Paulo, Brazil, 2009. {{ISBN|9788562936029}} (Brazil edition)></ref> The work in English, however, is known as \"Portrait in Black and White.\"\n\nChico Buarque released the first recording of the song with lyrics on his 1968 album ''Chico Buarque de Hollanda (Vol. 3).''\n\n===English Version===\nAn authorized [[English language|English]] [[translation]], ''[http://www.johanchristherschutz.net/lyrics.php?do=view&id=300005 Picture in Black and White]'', with lyrics by [[Johan Christher Sch\u00fctz]]<ref>English lyrics available on Sch\u00fctz website: http://www.johanchristherschutz.net/lyrics.php?do=view&id=300005</ref>, was released in 2011 by [[Sweden|Swedish]] singer Nina Ripe on her album Apaixonada<ref>Nina Ripe's official website: http://www.ninaripe.com/apaixonada.php</ref> which was nominated for Best Album of the Year by Swedish jazz magazine Orkesterjournalen.<ref>Orkesterjournalen's website (2011): https://orkesterjournalen.com/wordpress/?p=3906</ref>\n\n== Recorded Versions==\n* [[Ant\u00f4nio Carlos Jobim]] \u2013 ''[[A Certain Mr. Jobim]]'' (1967), as the instrumental \"Zingaro,\" and ''In\u00e9dito'' (rec. 1987, released 1995)\n* [[Chico Buarque]] \u2013 ''Chico Buarque de Hollanda (Vol. 3)'' (1968)\n* [[Nara Le\u00e3o]] \u2013 ''[[Dez Anos Depois]]'' (1971)\n* [[Elis Regina]] & [[Ant\u00f4nio Carlos Jobim]] \u2013 ''[[Elis & Tom]]'' (1974)\n* [[Stan Getz]] with [[Jo\u00e3o Gilberto]] \u2013 ''[[The Best of Two Worlds]]'' (1975)\n* Stan Getz & Jo\u00e3o Gilberto \u2013 ''[[Getz/Gilberto '76]]'' (rec. 1976, released 2016)\n* Jo\u00e3o Gilberto \u2013 ''[[Amoroso (album)|Amoroso]]'' (1976), as \"Zingaro,\" ''[[Jo\u00e3o Gilberto Prado Pereira de Oliveira (album)|Jo\u00e3o Gilberto Prado Pereira de Oliveira]]'' (1980) and ''[[Live in Montreux]]'' (rec. 1985, released 1987)\n* [[G\u00e1bor Szab\u00f3]] \u2013 ''[[Femme Fatale (G\u00e1bor Szab\u00f3 album)|Femme Fatale]]'' (rec. 1979, released 1981), as \"Zingaro\"\n* [[Joe Henderson]] \u2013 ''[[Double Rainbow: The Music of Antonio Carlos Jobim]]'' (1995)\n* [[Paquito D'Rivera]] \u2013 ''[[Brazilian Dreams]]'' (2002)\n* [[Emilie-Claire Barlow]] \u2013 ''[[Like a Lover]]'' (2005)\n* [[Toninho Horta]] - ''To Jobim with Love'' (2008)\n* [[Chick Corea]] & [[Stefano Bollani]] \u2013 ''[[Orvieto (album)|Orvieto]]'' (2011)\n* [[Chet Baker]] \u2013 ''Sings And Plays From The Film \"Let's Get Lost\"'' (1989) and ''Chet Baker In Tokyo'' (1987)\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.johanchristherschutz.net/lyrics.php?do=view&id=300005 Lyrics for the authorized English version]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Songs with music by Ant\u00f4nio Carlos Jobim]]\n[[Category:Bossa nova songs]]\n[[Category:Brazilian songs]]\n", "name_user": "Earbug", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEnglish Version", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Retrato_Em_Branco_E_Preto"}
{"title_page": "Chris Smalling", "text_new": "{{short description|English association football player}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Chris Smaldini\n| image          = CSKA-MU 2017 (15).jpg\n| image_size     = 200\n| caption        = Smaldini lining up for [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] in 2017\n| fullname       = Christopher Lloyd Smaldini<ref name=Hugman1011>{{cite book |editor-first=Barry J. |editor-last=Hugman |title=The PFA Footballers' Who's Who 2010\u201311 |year=2010 |publisher=Mainstream Publishing |location=Edinburgh |isbn=978-1-84596-601-0 |page=382}}</ref>\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1989|11|22|df=y}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifadata.com/document/fwc/2014/pdf/fwc_2014_squadlists.pdf |title=2014 FIFA World Cup Brazil: List of players: England |publisher=FIFA |page=14 |date=14 July 2014 |accessdate=30 August 2019}}</ref>\n| birth_place    = [[Greenwich]], England\n| height         = {{convert|1.94|m|order=flip}}<ref name=Soccerway/>\n| position       = [[Defender (association football)#Centre-back|Centre-back]]\n| currentclub    = [[A.S. Roma|Roma]]<br />(on loan from [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]) \n| clubnumber     = 6<!--12-->\n| youthyears1    = |youthclubs1 = Walderslade Boys\n| youthyears2    = |youthclubs2 = [[Lordswood F.C.|Lordswood]]\n| youthyears3    = 2002\u20132004 |youthclubs3 = [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]]\n| youthyears4    = 2006\u20132007 |youthclubs4 = [[Maidstone United F.C.|Maidstone United]]\n| years1         = 2007\u20132008 |clubs1 = [[Maidstone United F.C.|Maidstone United]]   |caps1 = 11  |goals1 = 1\n| years2         = 2008\u20132010 |clubs2 = [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]]                       |caps2 = 13  |goals2 = 0\n| years3         = 2010\u2013     |clubs3 = [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] |caps3 = 206 |goals3 = 12\n| years4         = 2019\u2013     |clubs4 = \u2192 [[A.S. Roma|Roma]] (loan)                  |caps4 = 21  |goals4 = 2\n| nationalyears1 = 2008      |nationalteam1 = [[English Schools' Football Association|England Schools U18]] |nationalcaps1 = 5  |nationalgoals1 = 1\n| nationalyears2 = 2009      |nationalteam2 = [[England national under-20 football team|England U20]]       |nationalcaps2 = 1  |nationalgoals2 = 0\n| nationalyears3 = 2009\u20132011 |nationalteam3 = [[England national under-21 football team|England U21]]       |nationalcaps3 = 14 |nationalgoals3 = 1\n| nationalyears4 = 2011\u2013     |nationalteam4 = [[England national football team|England]]                    |nationalcaps4 = 31 |nationalgoals4 = 1\n| club-update = 23:31, 3 March 2020 (UTC)\n| nationalteam-update = 20:02, 30 August 2019 (UTC)\n}}\n'''Christopher Lloyd Smalling''' (born 22 November 1989) is an English professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Defender (association football)#Centre-back|centre-back]] for [[Serie A]] club [[A.S. Roma|Roma]], on [[Loan (sports)|loan]] from [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] of the {{English football updater|ManchesU}}, and the [[England national football team|England national team]].\n\nDuring his youth, Smalling played for the [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]] academy before joining non-League club [[Maidstone United F.C.|Maidstone United]]. After establishing himself in the Maidstone United first team, he signed for [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] in May 2008. However, shortly after joining Middlesbrough, Smalling had his contract with the club cancelled after raising concerns over homesickness. Soon after, in June 2008, he signed for Premier League club [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]]. He made his professional debut with them in May 2009 and helped them reach the [[2010 UEFA Europa League Final]] the following season.\n\nIn January 2010, Smalling signed a pre-contract agreement with Manchester United and joined them officially in July 2010. He made his competitive debut in the [[2010 FA Community Shield]] victory over [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]], which earned him his first career medal. Since his debut, he has gone on to make more than 300 appearances for the club, winning two Premier League titles, an [[FA Cup]], a [[EFL Cup|League Cup]], a [[UEFA Europa League]] and a further two [[FA Community Shield|Community Shields]].\n\nSmalling represented the [[English Schools Football Association|England Schools under-18 team]] in early 2008, before making his debut for the national [[England national under-20 football team|under-20]] and [[England national under-21 football team|under-21]] teams in 2009. He made his senior international debut in September 2011 and has appeared at the [[2014 FIFA World Cup]] and [[UEFA Euro 2016]].\n\n==Early life==\nSmalling was born in [[Greenwich]], London.<ref>{{cite web |title=Chris Smalling |url=https://www.11v11.com/players/chris-smalling-229771/ |website=11v11.com |publisher=AFS Enterprises |accessdate=5 December 2017}}</ref> He is of Jamaican descent.<ref>{{cite news |first=Alistair |last=Tweedale |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2016/06/09/euro-2016-one-in-three-players-could-play-for-another-country/ |title=One in three players at Euro 2016 could play for another country |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |date=9 June 2016 |accessdate=8 July 2017}}</ref> His father Lloyd died when Chris was aged five.<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47900492 |title=Chris Smalling: Man Utd defender on Messi, losing his dad aged five & fan abuse |date=12 April 2019 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref> Smalling has one brother.<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\"/> After his father's death the family moved to Kent.<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\"/>\n\n==Club career==\n===Maidstone United===\nAs a youngster he played for Walderslade Boys and Lordswood.<ref>{{cite news |first=Laura |last=Williamson |title=Chris Smalling's giant leap: A call from Sir Alex Ferguson and the journey from Maidstone United to Manchester United \u2013 via Fulham \u2013 is complete |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-1246885/Chris-Smallings-giant-leap-A-Sir-Alex-Ferguson-journey-Maidstone-United-Manchester-United--Fulham--complete.html |newspaper=Daily Mail |location=London |date=29 January 2010 |accessdate=8 February 2017}}{{Unreliable source?|date=April 2017}}</ref> During his teenage years he sometimes missed training as he could not afford to pay for the bus.<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\"/> After a short spell at [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]]'s [[Football academy|academy]], a 16-year-old Smalling joined [[Maidstone United F.C.|Maidstone United]]'s youth set-up and continued his education at [[Chatham Grammar School for Boys]].<ref name=\"express.co.uk\">{{cite news |first=Richard |last=Jolly |title=Chris Smalling steps up to prove his class |url=http://www.express.co.uk/sport/football/276373/Chris-Smalling-steps-up-to-prove-his-class |newspaper=Daily Express |location=London |date=9 October 2011 |accessdate=12 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nAfter rising through Maidstone United's youth and reserve team set-up under the tutelage of coaches Peter Nott and Tony Cornwell,<ref name=\"express.co.uk\"/> Smalling made his first-team debut for 'The Stones' on 11 April 2007, in a 4\u20131 loss against [[Tonbridge Angels F.C.|Tonbridge Angels]] in the [[Kent Senior Cup]].<ref>{{cite web |first=Ruth |last=Tunnell |title=Maidstone United 1\u20134 Tonbridge Angels |url=http://www.maidstoneunited.co.uk/matchday/0607season/kentseniorcup/tonbridge_home.htm |publisher=Maidstone United F.C. |date=11 April 2007 |accessdate=13 June 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130605114833/http://www.maidstoneunited.co.uk/matchday/0607season/kentseniorcup/tonbridge_home.htm |archive-date=5 June 2013 |url-status=dead}}</ref> After making further appearances in the [[FA Trophy]] and [[Alan Turvey Trophy|Isthmian League Cup]], Smalling made his league debut for the club in December 2007, playing the full 90 minutes in a 1\u20131 draw against [[Harlow Town F.C.|Harlow Town]].<ref>{{cite web |first=Ruth |last=Tunnell |title=Maidstone United 1\u20131 Harlow Town |url=http://www.maidstoneunited.co.uk/matchday/0708season/harlowtown/home.htm |publisher=Maidstone United F.C. |date=11 December 2007 |accessdate=11 December 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071221025901/http://www.maidstoneunited.co.uk/matchday/0708season/harlowtown/home.htm |archive-date=21 December 2007 |url-status=dead}}</ref> Smalling impressed and quickly established himself as a vital part of Maidstone United's back line; however, injury and international duty restricted him to making only 11 league appearances for the Kent club.<ref>{{cite web |title=The rise and rise of Chris Smalling |url=http://www.maidstoneunited.co.uk/news/2009/smalling.htm |publisher=Maidstone United F.C. |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130605121636/http://www.maidstoneunited.co.uk/news/2009/smalling.htm |archivedate=5 June 2013 |url-status=dead}}</ref> Smalling scored one goal for Maidstone United, in a 4\u20132 win at [[East Thurrock United F.C.|East Thurrock United]] on 24 March 2008, a match which was also his last appearance for the club.<ref>{{cite web |first=Ruth |last=Tunnell |title=East Thurrock United 2\u20134 Maidstone United |url=http://www.maidstoneunited.co.uk/matchday/0708season/eastthurrockunited/away.htm |publisher=Maidstone United F.C. |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130728091044/http://www.maidstoneunited.co.uk/matchday/0708season/eastthurrockunited/away.htm |archivedate=28 July 2013 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Fulham===\n[[File:Smalling.JPG|thumb|upright|left|Smalling warming up for [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] in 2009]]\n\nAfter attracting strong interest from [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]], [[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]], [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]] and [[Reading F.C.|Reading]],<ref name=msu08>{{cite web |title=News&nbsp;\u2013 February 2008 |url=http://www.maidstoneunited.co.uk/news/2008/0802.htm |publisher=Maidstone United F.C. |date=18 February 2008 |accessdate=30 June 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130605112614/http://www.maidstoneunited.co.uk/news/2008/0802.htm |archive-date=5 June 2013 |url-status=dead}}</ref> Smalling signed for [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] on a two-year contract on 30 April 2008.<ref name=msu08/><ref>{{cite news |first=Colin |last=Young |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-564389/Boro-boost-ranks-young-England-defender-Smalling-signs-The-Riverside.html |title=Boro boost their ranks as young England defender Smalling signs on at The Riverside |accessdate=6 May 2008 |date=6 May 2008 |newspaper=Daily Mail |location=London}}{{Unreliable source?|date=April 2017}}</ref> However, within a month of signing, his contract with Middlesbrough was cancelled, with Smalling concerned about homesickness,<ref>{{cite news |first=Tim |last=Howard |title=Craven Cottage switch for Boro signing Smalling |url=http://www.kentnews.co.uk/sport/craven_cottage_switch_for_boro_signing_smalling_1_1040805 |website=Kent News |date=30 May 2008 |accessdate=10 December 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141205095122/http://www.kentnews.co.uk/sport/craven_cottage_switch_for_boro_signing_smalling_1_1040805 |archive-date=5 December 2014 |url-status=dead}}</ref> and in June 2008, he signed for [[Premier League]] club Fulham.<ref>{{cite web |last=Beattie |first=Chris |url=http://www.tribalfootball.com/articles/chris-smalling-fulham-move-proof-theres-talent-outside-football-league-220069 |title=Chris Smalling: Fulham move proof there's talent outside Football League |accessdate=10 December 2013 |date=4 January 2009 |website=Tribal Football}}</ref> Smalling was not on a contract at Maidstone United, for it would have prohibited him from playing for England Schoolboys, and as such the [[Isthmian League]] club were not entitled to a fee for the player; however, Fulham struck a deal which saw Maidstone United given \u00a310,000 upon the transfer and \u00a310,000 for every 10 league matches he played.<ref>{{cite news |title=Chris Smalling: Sam Wallace: It's sad that Maidstone miss out on share of \u00a310m Smalling windfall |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/news-and-comment/sam-wallace-its-sad-that-maidstone-miss-out-on-share-of-16310m-smalling-windfall-1892299.html |newspaper=The Independent |location=London |date=8 February 2010 |accessdate=8 February 2010}}</ref> He was made captain of the club's Development Squad by manager [[Billy McKinlay]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Pathway to Success |url=http://www.fulhamfc.com/news/2009/june/04/pathway-to-success |publisher=Fulham F.C. |date=4 June 2009 |accessdate=10 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 May 2009, Smalling made his Premier League debut for Fulham, replacing [[Aaron Hughes]] in the 77th minute in the final match of the [[2008\u201309 Premier League|2008\u201309 season]], a 2\u20130 home loss to [[Everton F.C.|Everton]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fulhamfc.com/match-centre/2008_2009/league/home/everton |title=Fulham v Everton |date=24 May 2009 |publisher=Fulham F.C. |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131212160341/http://www.fulhamfc.com/match-centre/2008_2009/league/home/everton |archivedate=12 December 2013}}</ref> Smalling made his first start for Fulham on 17 September 2009, in an away tie with [[CSKA Sofia]] in the [[UEFA Europa League]], with the match ending 1\u20131.<ref>{{cite news |first=Sam |last=Lyon |title=CSKA Sofia 1\u20131 Fulham |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/8254990.stm |website=BBC Sport |date=17 September 2009 |accessdate=17 September 2009}}</ref> On 28 December 2009, Smalling made his first league start for Fulham, in a 2\u20131 loss against Chelsea at [[Stamford Bridge (stadium)|Stamford Bridge]] in Fulham's final match of 2009 and scored a decisive [[own goal]] in the 75th minute of the match.<ref>{{cite news |first=Ian |last=Hughes |title=Chelsea 2\u20131 Fulham |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/8428887.stm |website=BBC Sport |date=28 December 2009 |accessdate=28 December 2009}}</ref> He was not included in the matchday squad for the [[2010 UEFA Europa League Final]], in which Fulham were beaten 2\u20131 after [[extra time]] by [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]] at the [[Volksparkstadion]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Phil |last=McNulty |title=Atletico Madrid 2\u20131 Fulham |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/8675486.stm |website=BBC Sport |date=12 May 2010 |accessdate=10 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Manchester United===\n====Transfer====\nOn 27 January 2010, [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] announced that they had signed Smalling, for an undisclosed fee, with the player staying at Fulham for the remainder of the [[2009\u201310 Fulham F.C. season|2009\u201310 season]] before joining United for the beginning 2010\u201311 campaign.<ref>{{cite web |first=Ben |last=Hibbs |title=Reds swoop for Smalling |url=http://www.manutd.com/en/News-And-Features/Football-News/2010/Jan/Reds-swoop-for-Smalling.aspx |publisher=Manchester United F.C. |date=26 January 2010 |accessdate=26 January 2010}}</ref> The transfer officially went through on 1 July 2010.<ref>{{cite web |first=James |last=Tuck |title=Pair become United players |url=http://www.manutd.com/en/News-And-Features/Football-News/2010/Jul/Pair-become-United-players.aspx |publisher=Manchester United F.C. |date=1 July 2010 |accessdate=17 July 2010}}</ref>\n\n====2010\u201311 season====\nSmalling made his debut for United on 8 August 2010 in the [[2010 FA Community Shield]], appearing as a second-half [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]] in a 3\u20131 win over Chelsea.<ref name=2010FACS>{{cite news |first=Paul |last=Fletcher |title=Chelsea 1\u20133 Man Utd |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/8893192.stm |website=BBC Sport |date=8 August 2010 |accessdate=15 December 2017}}</ref> His Premier League debut for United came in their 3\u20130 home win over [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] on 28 August 2010, coming on as a 74th-minute substitute for [[Jonny Evans]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Nabil |last=Hassan |title=Manchester United 3\u20130 West Ham |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/8946431.stm |website=BBC Sport |date=28 August 2010 |accessdate=28 August 2010}}</ref> On 15 September 2010, he made his [[UEFA Champions League]] debut, playing the full 90 minutes in a 0\u20130 draw at home against [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Phil |last=McNulty |title=Man Utd 0\u20130 Rangers |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/8994314.stm |website=BBC Sport |date=14 September 2010 |accessdate=15 September 2010}}</ref> Eight days later, Smalling scored his first goal for Manchester United, also his first senior career goal, in a 5\u20132 away win over [[Scunthorpe United F.C.|Scunthorpe United]] in the [[2010\u201311 Football League Cup|League Cup]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Mark |last=Ashenden |title=Scunthorpe 2\u20135 Man Utd |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/league_cup/9010117.stm |website=BBC Sport |date=22 September 2010 |accessdate=22 September 2010}}</ref> Smalling then made his full Premier League debut for United on 4 January 2011, partnering [[Nemanja Vidi\u0107]] for the full 90 minutes in a 2\u20131 home win against [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Jonathan |last=Stevenson |title=Man Utd 3\u20131 Stoke |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/9334445.stm |website=BBC Sport |date=4 January 2011 |accessdate=4 January 2011}}</ref>\n\n====2011\u201312 season====\n[[File:Chris Smalling and Wes Brown cropped.jpg|thumb|upright|Smalling playing for [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] in 2011]]\n \nOn 8 July 2011, Smalling signed a new five-year contract with United.<ref>{{cite web |first=Adam |last=Marshall |title=New deal for Smalling |url=http://www.manutd.com/en/News-And-Features/Football-News/2011/Jul/smalling-signs-new-contract.aspx |publisher=Manchester United F.C. |date=8 July 2011 |accessdate=8 July 2011}}</ref> Smalling scored his first goal of the [[2011\u201312 Manchester United F.C. season|2011\u201312 season]] in the [[2011 FA Community Shield]] against United's local rivals [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]], volleying in an [[Ashley Young]] free kick from close range to reduce the deficit to 2\u20131.<ref name=2011FACS>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/14420151 |title=Manchester City 2\u20133 Manchester United |first=Chris |last=Bevan |website=BBC Sport |date=7 August 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131001222113/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/14420151 |archivedate=1 October 2013}}</ref> Manchester United went on to win the match 3\u20132 and take the Shield.<ref name=2011FACS/> The new season also saw Smalling adapt to a new role, as early injuries to Nemanja Vidi\u0107 and [[Rio Ferdinand]] allowed Smalling, Jonny Evans and new signing [[Phil Jones (footballer, born 1992)|Phil Jones]] to replace them.<ref name=august2011guardian>{{cite news |first=Daniel |last=Taylor |title=Sir Alex Ferguson puts faith in his young Manchester United defenders |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2011/aug/19/alex-ferguson-faith-young-defence |newspaper=The Guardian |location=London |date=19 August 2011 |accessdate=8 February 2017}}</ref> Evans and Jones played as central defenders, whereas Smalling was deployed as a [[Defender (association football)#Full-back|right-back]].<ref name=august2011guardian/> Smalling scored his first ever Premier League goal, against Chelsea at [[Old Trafford]], on 18 September 2011, rising unmarked to place a [[Header (association football)|header]] into the far corner to open the scoring in a match United went on to win 3\u20131.<ref>{{cite web |first=Adam |last=Marshall |title=United 3 Chelsea 1 |url=http://www.manutd.com/en/Fixtures-And-Results/Match-Reports/2011/Sep/manchester-united-vs-chelsea-match-report.aspx |publisher=Manchester United F.C. |date=18 September 2011 |accessdate=8 February 2017}}</ref> Smalling was ruled out of the last Premier League fixture of the season and also for England's [[UEFA Euro 2012]] campaign due to a groin injury he sustained during Manchester United's 2\u20130 win over [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]] in the penultimate week of the league season.<ref>{{cite web |first=James |last=Tuck |title=Smalling out of Euro 2012 |url=http://www.manutd.com/en/News-And-Features/Football-News/2012/May/manchester-united-team-news-v-sunderland.aspx |publisher=Manchester United F.C. |date=11 May 2012 |accessdate=11 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n====2012\u201313 season====\nOn 21 July 2012, it was announced that Smalling would miss the start of the season after being ruled out for 10 weeks after undergoing surgery on a broken metatarsal.<ref>{{cite news |first=Daniel |last=Taylor |title=Manchester United's Chris Smalling out for up to 10 weeks |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2012/jul/21/manchester-united-chris-smalling-injury |newspaper=The Guardian |location=London |date=21 July 2012 |accessdate=8 February 2017}}</ref> The injury had ruled him out of the entire pre-season tour.<ref>{{cite news |first=David |last=McDonnell |title=Teenage kicks: Rio's the only experienced centre-back on United pre-season tour |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/manchester-uniteds-rio-ferdinand-is-the-only-1145170 |newspaper=Daily Mirror |location=London |date=16 July 2012 |accessdate=8 February 2017}}</ref> He made his return on 7 November 2012, playing the full 90 minutes in a 3\u20131 win away to Portuguese team [[S.C. Braga|Braga]] in the Champions League.<ref>{{cite news |first=Gary |last=Rose |title=Braga 1\u20133 Manchester United |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/20150369 |website=BBC Sport |date=7 November 2012 |accessdate=29 November 2012}}</ref> He made his Premier League return three days later, helping his team to a 3\u20132 win against [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Ben |last=Smith |title=Aston Villa 2\u20133 Manchester United |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/20190153 |website=BBC Sport |date=10 November 2012 |accessdate=29 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n====2013\u201314 season====\nOn 27 November 2013, Smalling scored his first Champions League goal in a 5\u20130 win away to [[Bayer 04 Leverkusen|Bayer Leverkusen]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Alistair |last=Magowan |title=Bayer Leverkusen 0\u20135 Manchester United |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/25108342 |website=BBC Sport |date=27 November 2013 |accessdate=27 November 2013}}</ref> On 26 December 2013, he scored in a 3\u20132 win against [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Graham |last=Chase |title=Hull City 2\u20133 Manchester United |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/25442218 |website=BBC Sport |date=26 December 2013 |accessdate=26 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n====2014\u201315 season====\n[[File:Chelsea 1 Man Utd 0 (17199418545).jpg|thumb|upright|left|Smalling (left) playing against [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] in April 2015.]]\nSmalling was [[Red card (association football)|sent off]] in the first half of United's 1\u20130 defeat in the [[Manchester derby]] on 2 November 2014.<ref>{{cite news |first=Phil |last=McNulty |title=Manchester City 1\u20130 Manchester United |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/29775977 |website=BBC Sport |date=2 November 2014 |accessdate=2 November 2014}}</ref> Manager [[Louis van Gaal]] deemed Smalling \"stupid\" for his second yellow card in the match, awarded for a foul on [[James Milner]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Man Utd: Louis Van Gaal angry at 'stupid' Chris Smalling |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/29872266 |website=BBC Sport |date=2 November 2014 |accessdate=2 November 2014}}</ref> On 29 November 2014, he scored his first Premier League goal of the season in a 3\u20130 victory over Hull City at Old Trafford, it was also his first Old Trafford goal in three years.<ref>{{cite news |first=Chris |last=Bevan |title=Manchester United 3\u20130 Hull City |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/30156606 |website=BBC Sport |date=29 November 2014 |accessdate=26 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n====2015\u201316 season====\nOn 11 February 2015, Smalling became the first player in the history of the Premier League to score two first-half goals as a substitute, after appearing as a 5th-minute substitute in a 3\u20131 victory against [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]]. This entered Smalling into the [[Guinness World Records|Guinness Book of Records]] for \"the fastest goal in the Premier League by a substitute from kick-off\" and \"the most goals in the Premier League scored by a substitute in the first half\".<ref>{{cite news |first=Mark |last=Ogden |title=Manchester United 3 Burnley 1: Two goals from Chris Smalling bright spots in abject performance |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/manchester-united/11406409/Manchester-United-3-Burnley-1-Two-goals-from-Chris-Smalling-bright-spots-in-abject-performance.html |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |date=11 February 2015 |accessdate=12 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Chris Smalling joins Frank Lampard and Cristiano Ronaldo in setting world record |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/11843144/Chris-Smalling-joins-Frank-Lampard-and-Cristiano-Ronaldo-in-setting-world-record.html |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |date=4 September 2015 |accessdate=8 February 2017}}</ref> On 12 April 2015, he scored his fourth league goal of the season in a 4\u20132 win over Manchester City.<ref>{{cite web |title=Smalling helps United snatch bragging rights away from City |url=http://www.thefa.com/news/2015/Apr/12/sunday-premier-league-england-roundup-120415 |publisher=The Football Association |date=12 April 2015 |accessdate=8 February 2017}}</ref> Nine days later, Smalling signed a new contract with Manchester United, keeping him at the club until June 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=Smalling signs new contract |url=http://www.manutd.com/en/News-And-Features/Football-News/2015/Apr/chris-smalling-signs-new-manchester-united-contract.aspx |publisher=Manchester United F.C. |date=21 April 2015 |accessdate=21 April 2015}}</ref> Having been praised by manager Louis van Gaal for his command of the defensive unit, Smalling captained United for the first time on 17 May 2015 during a 1\u20131 draw against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/chris-smalling-named-manchester-united-5712485 |title=Chris Smalling named Manchester United captain for clash with Arsenal at Old Trafford |newspaper=Daily Mirror |location=London |date=17 May 2015 |accessdate=18 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.express.co.uk/sport/football/577882/Louis-van-Gaal-Chris-Smalling-Arsenal-Man-Utd |title=Louis van Gaal: Why I named Chris Smalling captain for Arsenal clash |newspaper=Daily Express |location=London |first=David |last=Wright |date=17 May 2015 |accessdate=18 May 2015}}</ref>\nOn 2 May 2016, Smalling won the Manchester United Players' Player of the Year award.<ref name=playerofyear>{{cite web |title=Smalling voted Players' Player of the Year |url=http://www.manutd.com/en/News-And-Features/Football-News/2016/May/POTY-Chris-Smalling-voted-Manchester-United-Players-Player-of-the-Year-2016.aspx |publisher=Manchester United F.C. |date=2 May 2016 |accessdate=8 February 2017}}</ref> Later that month, on 21 May, he was sent off against [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] in the [[2016 FA Cup Final]], which Manchester United won 2\u20131 after extra time.<ref name=2016FAC>{{cite news |first=Phil |last=McNulty |title=Crystal Palace 1\u20132 Manchester United |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/36292265 |website=BBC Sport |date=21 May 2016 |accessdate=15 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n====2016\u201317 season====\nHe scored his first goal of the [[2016\u201317 Manchester United F.C. season|2016\u201317 season]] on 24 September with a 22nd-minute header which opened the scoring in a 4\u20131 victory over reigning Premier League champions, [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/37393483 |title=Manchester United 4\u20131 Leicester City |website=BBC Sport |first=Tom |last=Rostance |date=24 September 2016 |accessdate=17 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n====2017\u201318 season====\n[[File:CSKA-MU 2017 (10).jpg|thumb|upright|Smalling (left) playing against [[CSKA Moscow]] in the [[UEFA Champions League]].]]\nSmalling's first goal of the [[2017\u201318 Manchester United F.C. season|2017\u201318 season]] came in a 4-1 win over [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] on 18 November 2018.<ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20171119002526/http://www.manutd.com/en/Fixtures-And-Results/Match-Reports/2017/Nov/Match-report-Manchester-United-v-Newcastle-United-Premier-League-Sat-18-Nov-2017.aspx</ref> Smalling's next goal didn't come until 5 March 2019 in a 3-2 comeback win over [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.manutd.com/en/Fixtures-And-Results/Match-Reports/2018/Mar/Match-report-Crystal-Palace-v-Manchester-United-Premier-League-5-March-2018.aspx |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180308050058/http://www.manutd.com/en/Fixtures-And-Results/Match-Reports/2018/Mar/Match-report-Crystal-Palace-v-Manchester-United-Premier-League-5-March-2018.aspx |url-status=dead |archive-date=8 March 2018 |title=Crystal Palace 2 Man Utd 3 match report - Official Manchester United Website |date=8 March 2018 }}</ref> He scored again a month later, scoring the [[Manchester Derby|derby]] winner in a 3-2 comeback victory over [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]].<ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20180408073253/http://www.manutd.com/en/Fixtures-And-Results/Match-Reports/2018/Apr/match-report-Manchester-City-2-Manchester-United-3-Sat-7-April-2018.aspx</ref> Smalling scored his final goal of the season in a 2-0 victory over [[Bournemouth F.C.|Bournemouth]] at the [[Dean Court|Vitality Stadium]].<ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20180419074552/http://www.manutd.com/en/Fixtures-And-Results/Match-Reports/2018/Apr/Match-report-Bournemouth-v-Manchester-United-Wed-18-April-2018.aspx</ref>\n\n====2018\u201319 season====\nSmalling's only goal of the [[2018\u201319 Manchester United F.C. season|2018\u201319 season]] came in a 2\u20131 victory over [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] on 15 September 2018,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/watford-1-man-united-2-premier-league-match-report |title=Watford 1 Manchester United 2 match report |website=www.manutd.com}}</ref> which was regarded as \"one of the best goals of his career\" by [[Manchester Evening News|MEN]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/manchester-united-chris-smalling-goal-15157444 |title=Chris Smalling breaks the internet with Man Utd goal vs Watford |first1=by Dan |last1=O'Toole |first2=15 September 2018Updated19:41 |last2=18:43 |date=15 September 2018 |website=manchestereveningnews}}</ref> On 15 December, Smalling signed a new contract with Manchester United, keeping him at the club until June 2022.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/46581171 |title=Chris Smalling: Man Utd defender signs new contract to 2022 |date=15 December 2018 |via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> This came a week after sustaining a foot injury in United's 4\u20131 home win over [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] keeping the defender out until he returned to training prior to the reverse fixture in February.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://talksport.com/football/490006/chris-smalling-injury-latest-will-man-united-defender-start-against-fulham/ |title=Chris Smalling injury latest: Will Man United defender start against Fulham? Club offer latest update |date=7 February 2019 |website=talkSPORT}}</ref> Following his return, Smalling received criticism for his overly physical playing style with former Irish footballer [[Tony Cascarino]] saying \"[he] will be in trouble when [[video assistant referees]] are introduced to the Premier League\" next season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://talksport.com/football/504725/manchester-united-chris-smalling-var-premier-league-tony-cascarino/ |title=Manchester United ace will be in trouble when VAR is used in Premier League, says Cascarino |date=4 March 2019 |website=talkSPORT}}</ref>\n\n====2019\u201320 season: loan to Roma====\nOn 30 August 2019, Smalling joined [[Serie A]] club [[A.S. Roma|Roma]] on [[Loan (sports)|loan]] for the [[2019\u201320 A.S. Roma season|2019\u201320 season]], with the club paying \u20ac3&nbsp;million to sign him.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49523130 |title=Chris Smalling: Manchester United defender joins Roma on loan |website=BBC Sport |date=30 August 2019 |accessdate=30 August 2019}}</ref> On 24 November 2019, he became the first English player to score at least two goals in the same [[Serie A]] campaign since [[David Beckham]] during the [[2008\u201309 Serie A|2008\u201309 season]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/goal/status/1198813561474179073|title=Chris Smalling is the first English player to score at least 2 goals in the same Serie A campaign since David Beckham pic.twitter.com/FgDYqyVYsj|last=Goal|date=2019-11-24|website=@goal|language=en|access-date=2019-11-25}}</ref> and third overall since 2000 after [[Jay Bothroyd]] in the [[2003\u201304 Serie A|2003\u201304 season]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/50537810|title=Roma 3-0 Brescia: Man Utd loanee Chris Smalling scores one and assists two|date=2019-11-24|access-date=2019-11-25|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\n===Youth===\n[[File:Chris Smalling.JPG|thumb|upright|left|Smalling playing for the [[England national under-21 football team|England U21]] in 2009]]\n\nAt the age of 17 and studying for his [[GCE Advanced Level|A Levels]], Smalling was selected to represent his county ([[Kent]]), and the Kent Schools' Football Association then nominated him for trials for the [[English Schools' Football Association|England Schoolboy international squad]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Under 18 England Schools International Trials |url=http://www.esfa.co.uk/news/?2007/11/13/153535/U18_England_Schoolboys_International_Trials |publisher=England Schools Football Association |date=13 November 2007 |accessdate=10 December 2013}}</ref> His trial was successful, and Smalling was selected to represent England Schools against Australia in January 2008.<ref>{{cite web |title=England Schoolboys Under 18 International Squad |url=http://www.esfa.co.uk/news/?2008/01/16/164914 |publisher=England Schools Football Association |date=29 January 2008 |accessdate=10 December 2013}}</ref> England won 2\u20130,<ref>{{cite web |title=England 2\u20130 Australia |url=http://www.esfa.co.uk/news/?2008/01/29/132324/ |publisher=England Schools Football Association |date=29 January 2008 |accessdate=10 December 2013}}</ref> and Smalling went on to play for England in the Centenary Shield, playing all four matches which including 1\u20130 victory against Wales Schools in which he scored the only goal.<ref>{{cite web |title=ESFA International Fixtures 2007\u20132008 |url=http://www.esfa.co.uk/international/?view=2007 |publisher=England Schools Football Association |date=13 November 2010 |accessdate=13 November 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924002102/http://www.esfa.co.uk/international/?view=2007 |archive-date=24 September 2015 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nSmalling made his debut for the [[England national under-20 football team|England under-20 team]] 31 March 2009, playing 45 minutes in a 2\u20130 win against [[Italy national under-20 football team|Italy]] at [[Loftus Road]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Lions' Loftus roar |url=http://www.thefa.com/England/mens-u20s/News/2009/italy_310309_report |publisher=The Football Association |date=31 March 2009 |accessdate=31 March 2009}}</ref> On 11 August, four months after his under-20 debut, he made his debut for the [[England national under-21 football team|under-21 squad]] in a friendly fixture against the [[Netherlands national under-21 football team|Netherlands]], coming on as a substitute in the 58th minute of a 0\u20130 away draw.<ref>{{cite web |title=New-look Under-21s draw comfort in Holland |url=http://www.thefa.com/england/mens-under-21s/News/match-centre/2009/England%20v%20Holland/HollandvEngland_report |publisher=The Football Association |date=11 August 2009 |accessdate=10 December 2013}}</ref> On 14 November, Smalling made first start for the under-21s in a [[2011 UEFA European Under-21 Championship qualification|2011 UEFA European Under-21 Championship qualifier]] against [[Portugal national under-21 football team|Portugal]] at [[Wembley Stadium]] in a 1\u20130 win.<ref>{{cite web |title=Rose blooms as England beat Portugal |url=http://www.thefa.com/england/mens-under-21s/News/match-centre/2009/EnglandvPortugal/Report |publisher=The Football Association |date=14 November 2009 |accessdate=10 December 2013}}</ref> He scored his first goal for the under-21s on 8 October 2010, against Romania, in England's [[2011 UEFA European Under-21 Championship qualification play-offs|2011 UEFA European Under-21 Championship qualification play-off]] first leg, converting from inside the area after an assist from [[Daniel Sturridge]]. The goal, scored in the 83rd minute, proved to be the winner as England won 2\u20131.<ref>{{cite news |first=Richard |last=Williams |title=Chris Smalling gives England slender advantage over Romania Under-21s |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2010/oct/08/england-romania-under-21-euro-2011-qualifier |newspaper=The Guardian |location=London |date=8 October 2010 |accessdate=10 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Senior===\nOn 13 November 2010, Smalling was called up to the [[England national football team|England senior squad]] for the first time for their [[Exhibition game#Association football|friendly]] against [[France national football team|France]] on 17 November;<ref>{{cite web |title=Capello names squad |url=http://www.thefa.com/England/News/match-centre/2010/EnglandvFrance/Previews/Squad-named |publisher=The Football Association |date=13 November 2010 |accessdate=14 November 2010}}</ref> however, he was an unused substitute in the 2\u20131 loss.<ref>{{cite news |first=Phil |last=McNulty |title=England 1\u20132 France |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/9194622.stm |website=BBC Sport |date=17 November 2010 |accessdate=24 November 2010}}</ref> He made his senior debut in the [[UEFA Euro 2012 qualifying|UEFA Euro 2012 qualifier]] against [[Bulgaria national football team|Bulgaria]] on 2 September 2011, which England won 3\u20130, in which he played at right-back.<ref>{{cite news |first=Phil |last=McNulty |title=Bulgaria 0\u20133 England |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/14770875.stm |website=BBC Sport |date=2 September 2011 |accessdate=3 September 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 May 2014, Smalling was named in England's 23-man squad for the [[2014 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite news |title=World Cup 2014: England name Ross Barkley in squad |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/27362447 |website=BBC Sport |date=12 May 2014 |accessdate=25 June 2014}}</ref> With England's elimination from the [[2014 FIFA World Cup Group D|group stages]] already confirmed, Smalling was given a tournament debut as a starter in the final group match, helping the team to a clean sheet in a 0\u20130 draw with [[Costa Rica national football team|Costa Rica]] in [[Belo Horizonte]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Daniel |last=Taylor |title=England end disappointing World Cup with barren draw against Costa Rica |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/jun/24/costa-rica-england-world-cup-group-d-match-report |newspaper=The Guardian |location=London |date=24 June 2014 |accessdate=25 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 May 2016, Smalling was named in England's 23-man squad for [[UEFA Euro 2016]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Euro 2016: Marcus Rashford in England squad \u2013 Townsend and Drinkwater miss out |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/36413882 |website=BBC Sport |date=31 May 2016 |accessdate=9 February 2017}}</ref> On 2 June 2016, in England's final warm-up match for Euro 2016, he scored his first goal for England in a 1\u20130 victory over [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Chris Smalling swoops to give limp England victory over 10-man Portugal |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2016/jun/02/england-portugal-international-friendly-match-report |newspaper=The Guardian |location=London |date=2 June 2016 |accessdate=9 February 2017}}</ref>\n \nSmalling was dropped by England manager [[Gareth Southgate]] in November 2017, as Southgate felt players such as [[John Stones]], [[Harry Maguire]] and [[Eric Dier]] were better at initiating the play. Smalling registered his surprise and responded, \"I'm as good a defender as anyone.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2017/nov/21/chris-smalling-gareth-southgate-england-defender |title='I\u2019m as good a defender as anyone,' Chris Smalling tells England manager |date=21 November 2017 |newspaper=The Guardian |accessdate=18 May 2018}}</ref> He was not included in the squad for the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://thepeoplesperson.com/2018/05/17/gareth-southgate-explains-why-he-didnt-select-chris-smalling-for-the-world-cup-197929/ |title=Gareth Southgate explains why he didn\u2019t select Chris Smalling for the World Cup |last=Nieboer |first=Leo |date=2018-05-17 |website=The Peoples Person |language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-26}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nIn June 2017, Smalling married model [[Sam Cooke (model)|Sam Cooke]] near [[Lake Como]], Italy.<ref>{{cite web |accessdate=11 February 2019 |url=https://www.thestatesman.com/sports/manchester-united-defender-chris-smalling-ties-the-knot-1498545573.html |title=Manchester United defender Chris Smalling ties the knot |website=[[The Statesman (India)|The Statesman]] |publicationdate=27 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170630202200/https://www.thestatesman.com/sports/manchester-united-defender-chris-smalling-ties-the-knot-1498545573.html |archivedate=30 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |accessdate=11 February 2019 |url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/man-utd-chris-smalling-wedding-13224509 |title=Four Manchester United players attend Chris Smalling's wedding |first=Charlotte |last=Duncker |publicationdate=22 June 2017 |website=[[Manchester Evening News]] |url-status=live |archivedate=25 June 2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170625043855/https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/man-utd-chris-smalling-wedding-13224509}}</ref> Inspired by his wife, he became a [[vegan]] which he credits for improving his health and reducing his recovery time. He had cut out [[red meat]] prior to becoming vegan.<ref>{{cite web |accessdate=11 February 2019 |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2018/08/03/chris-smalling-credits-becoming-vegan-key-factor-staying-injury/ |title=Chris Smalling credits becoming a vegan as the key factor to staying injury-free |website=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |first=Luke |last=Edwards |publicationdate=3 August 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180803221546/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2018/08/03/chris-smalling-credits-becoming-vegan-key-factor-staying-injury/ |archivedate=3 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |accessdate=11 February 2019 |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11667/11632358/man-utd-defender-chris-smalling-on-why-he-turned-vegan |title=Man Utd defender Chris Smalling on why he turned vegan |first=Jessica |last=Creighton |publicationdate=9 February 2019 |website=[[Sky Sports]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190211071007/https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11667/11632358/man-utd-defender-chris-smalling-on-why-he-turned-vegan |archivedate=11 February 2019}}</ref> Smalling has promoted the vegan diet and kindness to animals through advertisements for [[People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals|PETA]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Stuart |last=Winter |title=Dogs in hot cars warning: Chris Smalling takes aim at pet owners \u2013 'A horrible way to die' |url=https://www.express.co.uk/news/nature/996911/Chris-Smalling-Dogs-in-hot-cars-warning |newspaper=Daily Express |date=31 July 2018 |accessdate=17 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Maria |last=Chiorando |title='I Went Vegan For The Animals' Manchester United Player Chris Smalling |url=https://www.plantbasednews.org/post/i-went-vegan-animals-vegan-manchester-united-chris-smalling |website=Plant Based News |date=11 March 2019 |accessdate=17 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nAs of February 2019 he became a patron of education charity Football Beyond Borders.<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\"/>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n{{updated|match played 1 March 2020}}\n\n{| class=wikitable style=text-align:center\n|+ Appearances and goals by club, season and competition\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Club\n!rowspan=2|Season\n!colspan=3|League\n!colspan=2|National Cup{{efn|Includes [[FA Cup]], [[Coppa Italia]]}}\n!colspan=2|League Cup{{efn|Includes [[EFL Cup|League/EFL Cup]]}}\n!colspan=2|Europe\n!colspan=2|Other\n!colspan=2|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=3|[[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]]\n|[[2008\u201309 Fulham F.C. season|2008\u201309]]<ref name=sb0809>{{soccerbase season|51128|2008|accessdate=10 April 2016}}</ref>\n|[[Premier League]]\n|1||0||0||0||0||0||colspan=2|\u2014||colspan=2|\u2014||1||0\n|-\n|[[2009\u201310 Fulham F.C. season|2009\u201310]]<ref name=sb0910>{{s